You know, I got a little story here, friends, I wanted to pass on out to you that I, the list that I know that happened up in our neck of the woods.
It was a man and his wife lived up there, pretty close neighbors there, and they were mighty nice people, just good old-fashioned, good-hearted country people.
And, uh,

So the missus, she decided there one day that her and the old man, they were kind of getting behind with their charity and first one thing or another, and she figured it was about time for them to do something for the community.
Well, the graveyard, the country graveyard there, it had kind of gone lacking, and she figured it needed cleaning off.
So they figured it would be a good thing to go down and clean off the graveyards.
It had a lot of grass and weeds and stuff growed up on it, so the old man, he got some holes and shovels and things.
They went down and looked it over and decided, well, the quickest way to get it cleaned would be just burn it off.
Well, it happened to be dry, and the old man, he looked around, you know, and there didn't seem to be too much wind.
So he got over on one side of the graveyard and set her on fire.
Got him some grass and got it to burn it good and just strode it all across there.
Well, friends, sure enough, it happened, as it happens lots of times.
There was more wind than they thought there was.
First thing he knew, the graveyard was clean all right, but so was the whole country around there.
And he'd come out near getting up into the little old town, our little town up there.
He'd come out near getting into the town.

We had to get out all the Forrester boys there and myself, along with the people that lived around the community and people that lived there in the little old town, and we had a hard time putting the fire out.
Well, they started out to do a good deed,
But it ended up doing an awful lot of damage.
Just think of all the little timber, little trees, young trees that were sent to the graveyard.

We just got to be more careful with these forests and grass and woods fires.

Friends, there's a few rules, a few simple rules that you can go by that will help us.
I say us because we are all in this thing.
One of us can't do it.
Two of us can't do it.
It takes all of us.
There's a few little simple rules.
First, you get a permit.
If the state law is required, you get this permit from your local fire warden or the forester fellow there.
That forester fellow, he'll be glad to help you.
And then when you go to burn brush or anything of that kind, pile it in small piles.
You can do a much better job burning it.
It'll burn up better and quicker.
You don't have all those big chunks and old burn-ins laying around the thing.
Pick a sort of a damp day.
Or you might hitch old roadie to the turning plow there and plow fur around.

fire from scattering out.

Have plenty of tools and water.
Be sure that your neighbor knows you're going to burn, and so he might run in and help you.
Shucks, I guess y'all already know all this stuff, friend, but I'm just merely reminding you of it, and just please be careful of them fires.
